sentences: Anderson was born on January 16, 1904, in Gilroy, California.
From 1914 to 1918 (age 9 to 13), Anderson attended St. Mary's Convent and studied voice.
From 1930 to 1945, Anderson lived at 724 East 52nd Place in Los Angeles, part of the 52nd Place Historic District.
Anderson's singing career began around 1921 with performances in Los Angeles.
In 1924, she toured with the musical Shuffle Along.
By 1925, she had performed in Cuba, the Cotton Club in New York City, and Los Angeles with the bands of Paul Howard, Curtis Mosby, and Sonny Clay.
In 1928, she sang in Australia with Clay's band and starred in Frank Sebastian's Cotton Club in Los Angeles in April.
From 1930 to early 1931, with pianist Earl Hines's band, Anderson performed in a 20-week residency at the Grand Terrace in Chicago, Illinois.
From 1930 to early 1931, with pianist Earl Hines's band, Anderson performed in a 20-week residency at the Grand Terrace in Chicago, Illinois.
In 1931, she became the first full-time vocalist in the Duke Ellington orchestra.
Her first appearance on record, "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)", recorded in 1932, was a hit.
She participated in Ellington's first European tour in 1933.
In 1940, she recorded "Solitude", "Mood Indigo", and "Stormy Weather".
One of the rare occasions Anderson sang independently of Ellington in this period was her performance of "All God's Children Got Rhythm" in the  Marx Brothers film A Day at the Races (1937) for MGM.
Owing to her chronic asthma, Anderson left Ellington's band in 1942.
Although her earliest obituary was dated December 27, 1949, later sources state her date of death as December 28, 1949.
Although her earliest obituary was dated December 27, 1949, later sources state her date of death as December 28, 1949.
Anderson often received prominent billing on advertisements for Ellington's appearances in theatres, auditoriums, arenas, and ballrooms, wherever the Ellington band toured in the 1930s.
Ellington wrote Music Is My Mistress (1973) with Anderson in mind.
